10,000 美元，巴里。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：这在 70 年代是一笔巨款。并不真地。</p><p>摩根森：不，不完全是。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：这在 50 年代甚至不算大钱。我的意思是，一年10块钱根本不算什么。这就是您对华尔街产生兴趣的原因吗？</p><p>摩根森：是的。所以我对自己说：“我没有一个富有的爸爸。我没有一个有钱的丈夫。我得自己做。那么我能做什么呢？</p><p>大约在那时，华尔街正在与平等就业机会委员会就性别歧视案件进行斗争。他们没有在街上雇佣足够的妇女。这是我们正在谈论的 80 年代初期。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：嗯，谢天谢地，问题已经解决了。</p><p>摩根森：是的。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：现在我们在金融领域实现了性别平等，谢谢。</p><p>摩根森：嗯，不完全是，但比以前好多了。反正…</p><p> RITHOLTZ：嗯，这绝对更好。</p><p>摩根森：所以他们必须开始雇用女性，因为他们输了这个案子。于是，我向大型经纪公司申请了推销员的职位——当时是添惠、美林、保德信……</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p>摩根森：我在添惠公司找到了一份工作。我得到这份工作的原因是因为我在电话测试中失败了。</p><p>里索兹：真的吗？嗯，你之前做过一些新闻工作，所以你不害怕向人们提问。</p><p>摩根森：是的。</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p>所以，现在是 80 年代，在巨大牛市的开始阶段，并不是 82 年的任何人都知道，接下来的 18 年将是一艘火箭飞船。</p><p>摩根森：等等，等等，等等。当我坐在 Dean Witter Reynolds 的椅子上时，道琼斯工业平均指数为 781 点。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：仍然低于 1,000。简直不可思议。</p><p>摩根森：是的，顺便说一句，这使得出售股票变得困难，因为人们仍处于回顾阶段。</p><p>里索兹：当然。</p><p>摩根森：他们没有期待。但是，1982 年 8 月——你还太年轻，不记得那件事……</p><p> RITHOLTZ：哦，不，我对此记得很清楚。</p><p>摩根森：轮到的时候。有点像，“好吧，股票太便宜了。这就是你想去的地方。”</p><p> RITHOLTZ：当时是 7 PE，对吧？</p><p>摩根森：是的。标准普尔指数的 7 PE。你知道，那是一个转折点。所以，我确实为这一举动做好了准备。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：你在添惠公司待了三年、四年？你在那里待了多久？</p><p>摩根森：我呆了三年。我经历过 1983 年科技股的熊市，你不记得了，当时个人电脑正处于初始阶段，计算规模正在变得越来越大，而且它们已经远远超出了自己的预期。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：当时我们还称它们为科技股吗？那句话是什么？</p><p>摩根森：你知道，我不知道。我认为是科技股。反正…</p><p> RITHOLTZ：我根本不记得那个熊市。</p><p>摩根森：是的，情况很糟糕。这是恶毒的。那是 1983 年夏天。所以，我经历了惨痛的教训，当你向人们推荐的股票因为你的公司说它们将告别而下跌时，会发生什么，而那些人会赔钱。我感觉很糟糕。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：嗯，他们不是告别，只是在接下来的六个月里不会。那就是问题所在。</p><p>摩根森：你知道，他们超前了。欣快感、势头变得太疯狂了。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：1983 年有欣快感吗？</p><p>摩根森：是的，当然。</p><p>里索兹：不是开玩笑。</p><p>摩根森：哦，是的，Eagle Computer，我的意思是，其中一些东西是雄心勃勃的。因此，当你有客户打电话给你说，天哪，我所有的钱都去哪儿了？这对我来说是一个巨大的创伤。我真的感觉很糟糕，我有点觉得如果你有太多的负罪感，也许不适合做生意。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：（笑）这就是让你重新回到新闻行业的原因吗？</p><p>摩根森：这就是让我回来的原因。然而，我确实有，或者说我现在掌握了很多关于华尔街世界如何运作的信息。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：这正是我下一步要去的地方，你有找到华尔街一些不为人知的操作的诀窍。你整个职业生涯都在这样做。作为经纪人，让你了解“嘿，这东西到底是如何运作的？”有多重要？</p><p>摩根森：非常重要，巴里。我的意思是，正如他们所说，你真的看到了内部运作方式，以及香肠是如何制作的。因此，我会看到场外交易柜台、场外股票交易柜台将如何推动股票并鼓励经纪人出售它们，并在其中投入大量佣金，因为一些大卖家正在进入市场而移动它们。市场。</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p>摩根森：这让我震惊，有几件事让我一直看到客户并没有被放在第一位。当然，还有我几年后写的那些相互矛盾的分析师。我亲眼目睹了这一点，我的客户也因此受到了伤害。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：所以让我们放一点阳光，让我们给这只猪涂一点口红。</p><p>到这里，已经是 40 年后的事了。街道的信托一侧在 80 年代很小，现在不仅很大，而且是增长最快的部分之一。虽然我们离性别平等还差得很远，但它肯定比以前更好了。</p><p>摩根森：现在比以前好多了，巴里。你不会让脱衣舞娘来参加人们的生日聚会，就像我当经纪人时看到的那样，好吗？</p><p>里索兹：难以置信。</p><p>摩根森：是的。我亲眼所见。</p><p>里索兹：我告诉办公室里的年轻人，去看《锅炉房》，去看《华尔街之狼》。这是真正的电影。铃声响起，那个世界就消失了。就像坏的部分一样，它消失了很好，但也有一些好的方面。就像培训项目一样，他们教人们什么是股票，​​什么是债券。他们曾经在大公司这样做过。与以前相比，这些现在就像小班一样。</p><p>摩根森：哦，真的吗，他们不再这样做了？</p><p> RITHOLTZ：他们这么做了，但不是原来的样子。因此，大约在您从华尔街转向新闻业的同时，杠杆收购热潮开始腾飞。它变得风靡一时。你当时在想什么？ “嘿，40 年后我要写一本书。”或者你是否在想，“这很有趣”，或者“问题来了”。当时你怎么看？</p><p>摩根森：当时，这看起来确实是对十年左右股票被低估的一个非常合理的反应。 20 世纪 70 年代，股市低迷。股票的死亡，你还记得那个封面。</p><p>里索兹：当然。 &#39;78，绝对。</p><p>摩根森：所以看起来这确实是对股市多年来被低估的一个相当合理的反应。因此，杠杆收购的初始阶段并不像现在那么有害，因为它们实际上接管了那些有价值的公司，坐在你可以看到的股价中，就像你提到的那样，七市盈率。</p><p>里索尔兹：是的。</p><p>摩根森：所以这确实是合理的。这是有道理的。这是之前发生的事情的自然结果。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：所以我们将更多地讨论《这些是掠夺者》这本书，但我必须提到你在书中真正关注的一系列名字。这些显然并不是私募股权的全部。还有很多，数百家其他公司。但阿波罗、黑石、卡莱尔和 KKR 似乎确实是焦点。是他们的规模、他们的行业、他们开展业务的方式吗？是什么让你找到了这四个人？</p><p>摩根森：嗯，首先是它们的尺寸，巴里。我的意思是，他们是这群人中的领导者。这些人和公司定下了基调，引领潮流。其他人模仿他们。 KKR 是 20 世纪 80 年代末 Kahuna 交易 RJR Nabisco 的幕后黑手。</p><p>因此，这是一群真正参与创建我们现在所说的私募股权的公司和人员。他们的规模和范围如此之大，以至于产生了巨大的影响。这就是我们关注它们的原因。</p><p>是的，有很多很多私募股权公司，但这些公司确实是定调的人。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：而且，您在书中提到了“门口的野蛮人”，该书重点关注 KKR 收购 RJR Nabisco。在当时，这有点不可思议，有人可以完全用低成本债务购买一家大型上市公司。这是否改变了比赛的走向？</p><p>一旦 RJR Nabisco 上场，是否意味着其他人也上场了？</p><p>摩根森：当然。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：这对接下来几十年发生的事情有何影响？</p><p>摩根森：是的。正如你所记得的，它也涉及国会。他们就此举行了听证会。我的意思是，当时这是一笔如此庞大的交易，确实让很多人感到紧张。有人研究过这些交易对工人和养老金意味着什么。这确实是质疑这些交易的影响的开始，但它们只是继续前进，继续前进。在 80 年代末，特别是在 1987 年经济崩溃之后，确实有一种感觉，我们真的不想插手此事。让我们让市场顺其自然吧。</p><p>事实上，我认为当时的财政部长说过，市场会解决这些问题，它们不会成为问题。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：市场最终总会解决这些问题，但这最终可能需要比预期更长的时间。</p><p>摩根森：是的。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：你提到他们产生了很大的影响，并且产生了很大的影响。他们还产生了大量的费用和大量的金钱。像 RJR Nabisco 这样的大型交易的金额是多少？</p><p>摩根森：嗯，当时听起来很大，但如果你现在回想起来，我不知道。我认为我们在书中有一个数字，可能是 7000 万美元或需要处理的费用。这甚至不是舍入误差。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：是的，这就是今天的零钱。</p><p>摩根森：这就是绕着钱走，对吧？</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p>摩根森：所以，它变得非常非常大，巴里。随着市场和资本池变得越来越大。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：我们稍后会讨论，随着这些公司变得越来越大，华尔街也变得越来越大，而这在某种程度上却在下面造成了一个空白。但这真的非常非常有趣，看看这一切是在没有人真正想要很多这样的公司的时候开始的。是的，其中一些公司几乎已经死了。</p><p>所以你在这本书的开头就用了一句话让我很开心。 “让抢劫开始吧” 那么，让我们从这里开始吧。这一切从哪里开始，什么时候从“嘿，我们将帮助这些似乎无法获得融资的公司提供资金”转变为全面的盗版和抢劫？</p><p>摩根森：嗯，有几件事很早就发生了，你可以看到它们的开始。这些收购不仅是为了找到那些可能被低估或表现不佳的公司，我们还可以将它们塑造成型，然后将它们出售，当他们这样做时，当他们在监视它们时，当他们在关注它们时，精简它们，改善它们的运营，可以从这些公司中收取大量费用。</p><p>因此，首先，私募股权公司通常会派人进入公司董事会。有时，这些董事会成员身份将为这些董事会成员带来收入。还有一种叫做监控费的东西，即被私募股权基金或公司收购的公司必须向公司支付其监控、监督以及向公司提供的管理专业知识的费用。</p><p>现在这是有道理的，因为他们接管了公司。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：他们可以做他们想做的事，他们是所有者。</p><p>摩根森：另外，他们大概非常擅长管理，他们知道自己在做什么，并且他们的目标是稍后出售以获取利润。</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p>摩根森：然而，监控费对他们来说确实有一种滥用的成分。它们通常采用 10 年期合同。因此公司同意在10年的时间内每年向私募股权公司支付一定数额的监管费。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：无论盈利能力还是他们的表现如何？</p><p>摩根森：哦，是的，不，这绝对是必要的。他们每年都这样做。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：最上面的一句话。</p><p>摩根森：因此，如果私募股权公司在五年后出售公司，公司仍然必须支付，仍然必须支付剩余的五年合同义务，即支付这些监控费用。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：现在，这不是吗？无论购买者是谁都知道这种情况正在发生，这不是会降低成本、购买价格吗？</p><p>摩根森：也许吧，但仍然如此。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：这是账面上的负债。</p><p>摩根森：但是，这仍然属于这些人。这是没有什么用的钱。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：成为国王真好。</p><p>摩根森：他们没有进行监控，但他们却获得报酬进行监控。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：还有其他类似的费用会破坏公司的稳定性吗？</p><p>摩根森：嗯，我想，我试着想，哦，好吧，好吧。嗯，首先，真正最终产生的巨额费用，这不是私募股权公司的费用，但许多此类交易的大问题是债务利息成本，好吗？</p><p>因此，当私募股权公司接管一家公司时，他们会给该公司带来大量债务。为了支付这些债务费用，其费用急剧增加。通常情况下，公司会提取——我的意思是公司——会以所谓的股利资本重组的形式提取资金。</p><p>他们会让公司背负沉重的债务，然后他们几乎会立即取出资金。这只是剥夺公司的一种方式——</p><p> RITHOLTZ：换句话说，当你说他们给公司带来债务时，他们就借了很多资本，所以现在公司拿着这笔现金，并承担了抵消负债，这意味着被收购的公司，以及 P/电子所有者/经理将从中收取费用。</p><p>摩根森：嗯，他们进行股息资本重组，这意味着他们将自己筹集的现金债务的一部分作为对自己的支付。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：谁把这笔钱借给了公司？</p><p>摩根森：可能是银行，可能是华尔街，可能是私人债务人，但它是——</p><p> RITHOLTZ：这通常也被证券化并出售到市场上？</p><p>摩根森：它可以是抵押贷款义务，现在是大额私人债务。但你已经有了这些股息回顾。 2007年，私募股权公司以股息资本重组的形式从公司提取了200亿美元。</p><p>里索兹：哇。</p><p>摩根森：到 2021 年，他们提取了 700 亿美元的股息资本重组。现在这是公司必须偿还的钱......</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p>摩根森：为偿还它而筹集的债务。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：这并不涉及公司正在做的事情。</p><p>摩根森：它不会进入公司的运营，并且会产生与之相关的利息成本。</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p>摩根森：这是我认为值得研究的另一个难题。所以，我们之前讨论过 RJR Nabisco。当你回顾 80 年代甚至 90 年代杠杆收购的历史时，你会发现它们似乎是很多鲜为人知、不一定面向消费者的公司、运输、物流和制造业。</p><p> RJR 是普通人最先知道的名字之一。</p><p>这种转变是如何发生的？大多数 80 年代杠杆收购的重点是什么？这些确实是非常不为人所知的事情。只是后来，或者至少在书中你是这样描述的，只是后来我们才知道它是家喻户晓的品牌、零售商和名字。如果你愿意的话，解释一下。</p><p>摩根森：嗯，我认为正在发生的事情 - 再说一次，我们之前讨论过一点，这些公司是被低估最严重的公司。</p><p>请记住，我们刚刚走出了一场非常严重的衰退。</p><p>因此，当时的工业公司可能受到经济衰退的严重损害。</p><p>因此，他们的市盈率可能低于标准普尔指数的平均水平 7。因此，这可能就是他们接管并更加关注他们的原因。</p><p>但同样，随着这种实践和过程演变成其他东西，它变得更多地与你所知道的一些大牌公司有关。</p><p>现在，一个重大的关键时刻是 90 年代初垃圾债券市场崩溃。 This was after the SNL crisis. SNLs had been persuaded to buy a lot of junk bonds. The market turned. Milken and Drexel Burnham collapsed and failed.</p><p> So you had this huge market maker in junk bonds disappear. Junk bond market went really into the toilet and that also then created a lot of distress in the market for companies that had borrowed from the junk bond market. And now you had those companies trading at very low prices.</p><p> So again, it was a distress situation that these companies took advantage of.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So how do you draw a distinction between LBO brands of private equity, the thing that some people call vulture capitalism, and credible mid-market banking and merchant banking that is really one of the few sources of capital for these mid-sized companies, given that Wall Street started chasing all the bigger firms?</p><p> MORGENSON: Well I think there is a right way and a wrong way to do this business.</p><p> And certainly there are many firms doing the right thing. As far as what that might mean, okay, less debt, okay? The debt that is levied onto these companies can be very damaging. And right now, Barry, we&#39;re going through a period of rising interest rates, and companies are experiencing distress, because much of this debt is floating. It&#39;s not fixed. And so what you need to remember is that the costs associated with borrowing money as a company when interest rates are zero is a different story than when interest rates are five.</p><p> So that is a huge part of the puzzle. So how about putting a little more equity into these deals instead of so much debt? How about putting more of your own skin in the game? Kind of a thing.</p><p> And I think the massive layoffs that often occur are very detrimental. I think that the asset stripping that has also occurred, pensions, for instance, are sold off, overfunded pensions get sold off and that goes into the private equity firm instead of into the company itself.</p><p> So I think you can avoid some of these practices very easily. You don&#39;t maybe get the returns that you do when you have all those pieces of the puzzle in place. But I think right now, we have to think about this as, is it a sustainable business model that you fire a lot of workers, that you strip pensions and health benefits, that you levy the debt on these companies, and that you want to sell them in five years, which is short-termism, you know, that we often sort of deplore in the stock market.</p><p> Is that really a business model that can work for the long haul?</p><p> So, when private equity really was ramping up in the &#39;80s and &#39;90s, it was essentially an institutional allocation. This wasn&#39;t a mom-and-pop investment. Today, that&#39;s changed. It&#39;s really attracting a lot of retail dollars. How is that working out?</p><p> MORGENSON: Well, you know, it&#39;s interesting. For years, decades, as you say, this was an investing strategy that was limited to sophisticated investors, high net worth individuals, people who could take it, stand the fact that it&#39;s opaque, that it has high fees, that it is not quite as investing in an S&amp;P 500 stock fund, and not that simple.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> MORGENSON: But now it is encroaching onto the mom and pop in 401(k)s. The Labor Department under Donald Trump did open the door for private equity to get into 401(k)s. It had been prevented, had been barred from that before because of this fiduciary duty idea and also because of the opacity of these instruments.</p><p> But so yes, you have it starting to seep into what we might call the high net worth retail market. Some of these, the Blackstone BREIT is a perfect example of that. That&#39;s a real estate investment trust that is a Blackstone entity.</p><p> And it has really done a lot to attract the high net worth retail customers into that. I think that private equity sees this as an opportunity, because they&#39;re not really growing the institutional aspect of their business. Pension funds, perhaps, maybe aren&#39;t growing as much as they need them to. And so, this is a ripe market for them.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Clearly, 401(k) is not a much faster growing part of the allocation landscape than either direct benefits or pensions, if anything, that side of the street is shrinking dramatically.</p><p> Let&#39;s talk about some of the new areas that private equity seems to be playing in. The book talks about emergency care and ER rooms that have been privatized. I always think of ER and those sorts of emergency services as a service, as a community good, not a for-profit model, am I naïve in not realizing we could monetize emergencies? Or should this be kept out of private asset allocators&#39; hands?</p><p> MORGENSON: This is a really, really crucial question for the whole private equity industry. Now, They have seized on healthcare as a huge industry to really dive into, to invest in. And you know why that is? Because it&#39;s 17% of gross domestic product.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right, giant.</p><p> MORGENSON: So it&#39;s a big, big pool of potential money.</p><p> So you have private equity rolling up doctors&#39; practices, you have private equity going into dermatology practices.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Imaging, MRI, CAT scans, all that.</p><p> MORGENSON: Anesthesiology is another big one. And yes, emergency departments is another. And the difficulty with healthcare is that you are not supposed to put profits ahead of patients.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So, let&#39;s talk about hospitals. I don&#39;t understand how all these not-for-profit hospitals get purchased and rolled up into a chain of not-for-profit hospitals that are managed for profitability. That seems to be counterintuitive.</p><p> Tell us a little bit about what&#39;s going on there.</p><p> MORGENSON: Well, what we&#39;re really talking about, Barry, is the staffing companies that staff the hospitals. So, private equity is not buying the emergency departments. What private equity is doing is operating the emergency departments.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Similar to how hotels operate.</p><p> MORGENSON: For the hospital. And it&#39;s like any staffing You know, you&#39;re a big whatever. You hire a staffing company to help you find people, okay. So there are two major players in emergency departments. One is Team Health, and the other is Envision. Envision is owned by KKR, and Team Health is Blackstone.</p><p> And they control– and other smaller private equity firms– control 40% of the nation&#39;s emergency departments.</p><p> Wow, that&#39;s a lot. Now, you don&#39;t know this when you go to the emergency department. The hospital hires them. Of course they say to the hospital, we&#39;re going to improve your profitability. We&#39;re going to help you make more money. They&#39;ll say improve patient care. But the doctors that I have spoken to in emergency medicine say that&#39;s absolutely not the case.</p><p> That when the private equity firms come in, they tell them how to do their business. They tell them how to code for patient billing.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Well, they&#39;re medical experts, aren&#39;t they, private equity? Don&#39;t they have a specialty in emergency care?</p><p> MORGENSON: No, I think they have a specialty in financing.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: They&#39;re financers, I&#39;m sorry.</p><p> MORGENSON: Yes, they have a specialty in financing.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Excuse me for my…</p><p> MORGENSON: And making a return.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: This is horrifying, I have to tell you. I don&#39;t have a problem with private equity pushing into real estate and other areas, but emergency rooms seem sort of …</p><p> MORGENSON: Right, I mean if you&#39;re talking about the coffee and doughnut that private equity owns, okay. If you don&#39;t like the coffee and the doughnut, you&#39;ll go somewhere else. But if you&#39;re in need of an emergency department, and this is the only one in your town, and you have to go there, and it&#39;s run by an equity firm that is putting profits ahead of patients, that&#39;s a problem.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: And this has become very big, not necessarily in big cities, but in the South, in rural areas, in places that have very limited healthcare options and a shortage of doctors, it&#39;s not like there&#39;s the option of saying, “Oh, I don&#39;t like Southwestern General. I&#39;m going to go to Northeastern General and that&#39;s a better emergency room.”</p><p> This is usually one of the only games in town, is that right?</p><p> MORGENSON: Absolutely. Rural hospitals have really been hit by this practice.</p><p> The other thing, Barry, is that they don&#39;t put the name on the door …</p><p> RITHOLTZ: No.</p><p> MORGENSON: Over the emergency department. They don&#39;t say Team Health is here, or they don&#39;t say Envision or KKR or Blackstone is running this. And so try to find out if your emergency department is run by one of these companies. It&#39;s very difficult to do.</p><p> So again, it&#39;s opaque. Again, the consumer does not know that this is happening. And so much of what private equity has taken over is kind of like this, a stealth takeover, because they don&#39;t put their names on the door.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So let&#39;s talk about senior living. Since when are old folks&#39; homes a profit center? Tell us about that.</p><p> MORGENSON: This is perhaps the biggest crisis, I think. And it really became very evident in a 2021 study by academics, I think University of Chicago, UPenn, NYU, that studied long-term mortality at nursing homes that were owned by private equity and compared that with nursing homes.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: They&#39;re so much more efficient, their mortality rates have to be much better, right?</p><p> MORGENSON: They&#39;re so much more efficient because maybe they hire fewer people to take care of the residents that the mortality rate is higher.</p><p> The mortality rate is 10%.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Really, that&#39;s a big number.</p><p> MORGENSON: 10%, and so these academics found that there were 20,000 lives that they said were lost because at private equity-owned nursing homes, nursing facilities. And so you have the situation the academics said where the focus, the extreme focus on cost cutting meant lower staffs, meant lesser care, essentially translated to lesser care.</p><p> And this was just a striking, striking study of the difference between, and they were comparing it to other for-profit nursing homes. So this was not just for-profit versus non-profit. This was private equity, for-profit and non-profit.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: How did private equity healthcare, senior living, nursing homes, ERs, hospitals, do during the COVID pandemic?</p><p>摩根森：嗯，他们做得很好，因为他们从政府那里得到了很多 CARES 法案的资金。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：我的意思是，护理本身是如何进行的？疫情期间他们表现如何？</p><p>摩根森：嗯，如你所知，医疗保健是一场灾难。部分原因是我们对大流行病毫无准备。</p><p>巴里，我会争辩说，我们如此措手不及的原因之一是因为自 2000 年代中期以来，医疗保健一直是私募股权的关注焦点。好吧，HCA，完美的例子，这是一家在杠杆收购中私有化的公司。所以你所拥有的是这些公司，再次专注于削减成本。</p><p>因此，他们不太可能囤积个人防护装备、口罩，购买呼吸机，为大流行做准备。而事实上……</p><p> RITHOLTZ：嗯，那些东西都是要花钱的。</p><p>摩根森：那要花钱。放在架子上的是钱。这些家伙不喜欢坐在架子上的钱。因此，您实际上在国会进行了一项研究，研究了如果我们经历一场大流行病可能会发生什么。这是在 2005 年或 2006 年。它说，“我们需要储备更多设备。”</p><p> RITHOLTZ：你让盖茨在 2015 年的研究中说了同样的话？即时库存不起作用，因为在大流行期间你无法获得东西。结果非常准确。</p><p> MORGENSON: Right.但是在 2020 年之前的那些年里，当整个世界在 3 月崩溃时，在它到来之前的那些年里，我们经历了某种程度的医疗保健消耗，医疗保健公司因为削减脂肪、削减成本而流血.</p><p> RITHOLTZ：所以，我现在要问你一个问题，但它也适用于保险，我们稍后会讨论这个问题。但是在联邦层面有监管机构。每个州都有医疗委员会。这种死亡率和健康结果都更差的医疗保健如何获利，它们如何通过州监管机构获得？</p><p>你会想象全州的监管医疗委员会不会真的容忍这种情况。</p><p>摩根森：这是一个价值 64 万亿美元的问题，巴里，我很乐意让你问问每一位州检察长，例如，你为什么不追求营利性医学？</p><p>全国 30 多个州的法规禁止所谓的公司医疗实践。这些法律在 100 年前生效，当时你有江湖医生向人们展示疯狂的药方。他们决定，这些州决定，你不能在病人护理之前获得潜在的利润。</p><p>所以医生实际上必须经营这些组织。据推测，这将避免将利润置于患者之上的问题。但是，非常非常非常少的州 AG 执行了禁止公司行医的法律。当他们确实带来案件时，他们的手腕拍击是如此之小和如此简约，以至于他们将其交付给这些公司，以至于这甚至不是开展业务的成本。所以就像，好吧，好吧，我会再做一次，下次更大。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：让我们谈谈保险吧。保险政策的东西似乎绝对令人震惊。私募是如何涉足保险领域的？同样，这是一个监管非常严格的行业，拥有独立的、非常强大的全州监督小组和委员会。</p><p>保险界正在发生什么？</p><p>摩根森：嗯，我很想听听你说它在州方面非常稳健。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：至少它是这样呈现的。与尝试获得保险许可的人交谈，或者在随后的诉讼中是否未能支付保单。保单持有人似乎有一些选择，特别是如果你有一个乐于接受的州长或州检察长可以通过这些保险委员会施加压力，尽管也许我生活在过去。</p><p>摩根森：嗯，我认为它参差不齐。我们只是说有些州的监管很激进，但也有很多州没有。</p><p>正如您可能猜到的那样，其中一些公司涌向那些监管更加简约的州。现在，保险公司被私人股本所有的问题是，你可以理解他们为什么想要拥有它们，因为这是一个资产池，这是一个他们可以真正产生巨大利润的资金池。它不像银行，它不是快钱或热钱，它不太可能迅速离开，巴里，就像我们在最近的一些银行问题中看到的那样。因此，对于这些公司和这些私募股权公司来说，保险公司确实是非常稳定的巨大资金池。这很有趣，因为在保险方面你应该非常保守。大多数人，我认为，大多数购买保险单的人真的更希望他们的保险公司是一个保守的实体，它不承担风险，我们不会在这里摇摆不定。</p><p>你知道，是的，如果我能获得更高的收益，那就太棒了，但我真的很想知道，当我提出索赔时，我会得到赔付。</p><p>所以这些公司正在做的是购买这些保险公司，他们也在购买养老金资产，巴里，所以一家公司有养老金，比方说是洛克希德、百时美施贵宝或几家。私募股权公司将购买这些养老金义务。</p><p> Lockheed 或 Bristol-Myers 将其从账簿上删除，他们很高兴，他们转移了这些义务对他们带来的风险，而私募股权公司接管了该风险。但是现在如果养老金失败，你没有养老金福利担保公司支持你。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：那么，一家公司可以通过将其出售给第三方来摆脱 PBG 的约束吗？</p><p>摩根森：正确。这被称为养老金风险转移，它们一直在疯狂发生。私募股权公司是进行大量养老金风险转移的公司。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：这真的很有趣。</p><p>摩根森：因此，百时美施贵宝、洛克希德或库尔斯的养老金领取者是另一个真正依靠私募股权为他们未来的养老金、退休生活和需要时的支出做正确事情的人。</p><p>而且，我认为，我们真的不了解其全部性质。不幸的是，我们将会看到，如果这些私募股权公司对其保险公司的部分投资开始出现问题，我们可能会看到利率上升带来的一些问题。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：这些独立投资是否意味着您作为受托人代表养老金领取者进行管理。然后你就不能转过身来，用你在街上卖的任何垃圾纸来装满养老金吗？或者会发生这种情况吗？</p><p>摩根森：那确实发生了。现在，他们确实必须在向保险监管机构提交的法定文件中披露他们在保险公司的投资组合中有多少是相关交易或相关股票或债券或抵押贷款或其他任何东西。</p><p>所以他们确实必须披露这一点，但我猜很少有人会阅读这些披露。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：非常有趣。让我们谈谈本世纪的保险交易。 Executive Life 是怎么回事？那里发生了什么，它是如何偏离轨道的？</p><p>摩根森：《高管生活》是本书的开头，因为它是一次巨大的失败，当然，它是在垃圾债券崩溃时出现的。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：但这之前是一家备受推崇的 AAA 保险公司。</p><p>摩根森：这是一家评级很高的保险公司。它的评分最高。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：一个加号。</p><p>摩根森：但它是由一个人经营的，他就是我们过去常说的枪手。</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p>摩根森：他是一个比一般保险公司高管更愿意冒险的人。他还从 Drexel 购买了大量垃圾债券。当他们出售这些质量略低的债券时，他是他们的主要客户之一……</p><p> RITHOLTZ：质量略低。</p><p>摩根森：鲜为人知的公司。他是来买的。</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p>摩根森：所以他的公司，他的保险公司，有大量的垃圾债券。</p><p>当市场转向时，对他来说是可怕的。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：所以这确实与私募股权分开。这只是一位本应保守的保险业高管的糟糕管理。再一次，问题是，当一家保守的保险公司购买垃圾时，监管机构在哪里？</p><p>我的意思是，它就在名字中，他们甚至没有隐藏它，垃圾债券。 Executive Life 发生了什么？他们爆炸了。</p><p>摩根森：他们爆炸了。加利福尼亚州保险部当时由约翰·加拉门迪 (John Garamendi) 管理，他现在是华盛顿加利福尼亚州众议院的代表。而他刚刚上任。这是一个新当选的职位。在此之前，它已被州长任命。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：你必须跑去监督？</p><p> MORGENSON：是的，你必须跑去保险公司……</p><p> RITHOLTZ：我不知道那会怎样。</p><p>摩根森：不管怎么说，他赢得了这份大工作，他一进门，垃圾债券就暴跌，每个人都在关心 Executive Life，它是否能够支付保单持有人。于是他接管了公司。现在，记住，巴里，他可能在底部或非常接近底部抓住了它，好吗？所以垃圾债券在他接手后开始卷土重来。因此，如果它是用另一种方式解决的，那是有可能的。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：就像重组或……</p><p>摩根森：就像重组一样，保单持有人可能没有失去他们最终失去的东西。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：保单持有人的发型是怎样的？</p><p>摩根森：你知道，直到今天它仍然存在，我们不知道，但它肯定在三四十亿美元左右，甚至可能更高。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：那看起来是多少百分比？三分之一，一半？</p><p>这是一个很大的块，对吧？</p><p>摩根森：对很多人来说，这是一大笔钱。你知道，我的意思是，我知道在某些情况下，某些保单持有人的理发率是 40%。很难，你知道，在这件事上获得数字，他们真的不想提供帮助。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：然后，告诉我们一条疯狂的规则：“好吧，现在我们要销毁所有与此相关的文件。” What the hell was that?</p><p>摩根森：嗯，好的。让我们记住，这发生在 1991 年。保险部门在 1991 年接管了它。然后我们有了 Apollo，Leon Black 的新公司，在他逃离 Drexel 之后，残骸在 Drexel 燃烧。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：Drexel 倒闭了。</p><p>摩根森：德雷塞尔公司倒闭了。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：可以说这与他没有任何关系。这主要是米尔肯的问题。</p><p>摩根森：不，他不在垃圾债券领域。他是一名企业财务人员。他正在为这些公司筹集资金。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：那么，他是逃跑了，还是只是说，“嘿，我们去创办我们自己的公司吧”？</p><p>摩根森：是的，让我们去创办我们自己的公司。</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> MORGENSON: Right.但是，我的意思是，这显然是一个可怕的情况。所以，无论如何，长话短说，他最终得到了这个庞大的垃圾债券投资组合，这是他投入 Fred Carr 的大量文件——这是经营 Executive Life 的人的名字——Apollo 真正了解的文件这是什么。他们知道这些数字。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：Leon 是一名销售员和金融家。</p><p>摩根森：他是财务人员。</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p>摩根森：所以，他知道这些数字。他了解这些公司。所以，他知道他们很痛苦，他们可以重组和重组。</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p>摩根森：因此，他购买了这个垃圾债券组合。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：总之，他住在纽约，对吧？</p><p>摩根森：他住在纽约。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：行政生活在加利福尼亚。</p><p>摩根森：是的，是的。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：但是由于与 Drexel 的关系，他来到加利福尼亚并说，“我们想买这种垃圾纸”，或者他们举行了拍卖会？ How did it go?</p><p>摩根森：嗯，实际上是一家法国银行。他们代表银行。他们担任银行的投资经理，因此它将被这家法国银行接管。但无论如何，所以保险部卖掉了它，绝对便宜地卖掉了公司。</p><p>因此，购买它的人，在这种情况下，即法国银行和阿波罗，能够乘坐这些垃圾债券的复苏。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：那么，当加州代表保单持有人出售这个产品时，是否有任何强制规定，“嘿，你必须至少支付 0.90 美元，”或者是否有任何要求？他们以低价出售它。加州代表加州保险委员会应该经营的人将它附加到新业主的哪些车手？</p><p>摩根森：好吧，加利福尼亚州当时说，“我们认为这很重要。你将至少得到 0.90 美元的美元。每个人都会得到至少 0.90 美元的美元。”那是他们的故事，他们坚持这一点。</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p>摩根森：他们就是这么说的。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：但他们并不要求将其作为购买的一部分。</p><p>摩根森：嗯，这就是他们所说的作为购买的一部分将要发生的事情。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：我可以说各种各样的话，但直到我签署一份合同，上面写着“我保证我将至少向每位股东支付 90 美分”，这只是空话。</p><p>摩根森：是的，嗯，发生的事情是，很多人没有得到 90 美分的美元。有相当多的人武装起来，希望对此进行调查。你看着某个时刻，然后说，“如果保险公司拿保单持有人的钱冒险，就会发生这种情况。”</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.这一切都可以追溯到枪手，而不是保守的操作员。还有一些其他的监管问题让我一直很着迷。首先是私募股权的业绩报告。华尔街内部有很多批评，充其量它是激进的，最坏的情况它只是一个幻想。</p><p>如果您将资金投入私募股权，您并不关心他们何时进行购买。将资金投入私募股权的捐赠基金和养老金的内部收益率。他们不关心那个，但这似乎是他们报告的方式。</p><p>告诉我们一些性能数据是如何产生的。我什至不知道如何描述它。</p><p>摩根森：嗯，这些是私营公司，而不是公司本身。如您所知，它们是公开交易的。但当他们收购一家公司并将其投入基金时，它就是一家私人公司。因此，他们如何标记那家公司的价值是，那里有回旋余地，巴里。他们可以以某种方式对它进行估值，让我们这么说吧，股票市场不会对其进行估值。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：但是你是在具体评估你购买它的方式，然后如果它在五年后卖掉，那就是一笔硬钱。为什么两者之间有这么大的回旋余地？</p><p>摩根森：因为在你真正购买公司之前，你还没有买家告诉你它的确切价值。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：真的很有趣。让我们谈谈税收漏洞。</p><p>私募股权、对冲基金和风险投资的附带利益税漏洞到底怎么来的？你说的是所有纳税人中的一小部分。为什么要特殊对待？</p><p>摩根森：我认为，它最初是作为对房地产的特殊待遇，随着私募股权风险投资领域的扩张，它逐渐演变成更大的事情。从本质上讲，这些公司的经理和高管最终支付的非常非常慷慨的支出比你我低得多。</p><p>这是一个漏洞，人们几十年来一直试图摆脱它。我们已经就此举行了国会听证会。然而它继续留在书本上。天哪，当人们说，看，也许我们应该重新考虑这个，而不是让这些人——我的意思是，这就像亿万富翁造币机对这些人实行这种较低的税率时，他们会哭泣？</p><p> RITHOLTZ：当你基本上可以支付 23% 时，谁愿意支付 37%？当然，他们在游说者身上花钱。将我的税减半，我在哪里注册？哦，等等，我无权访问它。</p><p>摩根森：创办一家私募股权公司，巴里。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：所以这就是我们要做的。我们将成立一家私募股权公司，我们将购买养老金，并将其纳入标准普尔 500 指数，并花费我们五个 BP 来管理它。如果你那样接近它，那里有很多脂肪。</p><p>因此，让我们谈谈一些阻力。我看到了一些批评和一些东西。我想听听你的看法。</p><p>首先，我们早些时候谈到了这一点。大公司和杠杆收购、杠杆收购与中间市场、向小公司提供资本和股权的小型私募股权公司有很大不同吗？一些人批评说，你画画的方式不是太宽泛了吗？</p><p>摩根森：嗯，如果你看看这些公司，这些人，这些真正的行业巨头。在商业页面上庆祝，你知道，他们一直在电视上。我的意思是，这些人是这个行业的领路人。</p><p>现在，再一次，有其他人做得对，而且做得更好，是的。</p><p>但是你想关注的是，这些人定下了基调。这些人说，“这就是我们将如何运作”，而这些人确实具有最大的影响力，巴里，因为他们的规模。这就是为什么我们真正想要关注它们的原因。</p><p>所以当你有两家公司控制这个国家 30% 的急诊部门时。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：很多。</p><p>摩根森：这就是你关注大公司的原因。他们有很大的影响，所以这就是我们这样做的原因。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：让我们谈谈财富不平等。你们把很多事情归咎于私募股权让事情变得更糟。但我看看财富不平等和工资不平等，这是很多事情。这是低工资和最低工资，而且一直没有上涨。这是企业避税。这是将税收负担从富人和公司转移到中产阶级。</p><p>我们不是把加剧美国财富不平等的责任归咎于私人股本吗？</p><p> MORGENSON：嗯，我们认为将它们包括在组合中很重要的原因是我们还没有真正进行过讨论。我的意思是，私募股权并没有真正被提及为造成美国贫富差距的一种力量。你会听说工作外包，你会听说公司去爱尔兰这样他们就不必支付高额税款。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：双重荷兰人，不管它叫什么东西。</p><p>摩根森：所以有很多讨论，当然还有工会的削弱或减少，所以你在工人和公司之间没有权力平衡。但是你看看这些力量背后的一些力量，对吧？</p><p>养老金就是一个很好的例子。如果你开始看到私募股权公司接管养老金，你知道，或者剥夺他们破产公司的养老金，那肯定是财富鸿沟，对吧？这对美国大街上的普通人来说肯定会产生影响，我认为我们还没有真正检查过。</p><p>所以你只需要看看一些做法的背后。</p><p> When you have retailing, that&#39;s a big force, a big area that private equity has been very forceful in. Almost 600,000 jobs lost in retailing. Now, yes, some of that would have happened with the shift to online. But honestly, there have been consequences like that. So you look at that, and then you look at the problems with health care and what it&#39;s doing to patients. And so I do think that it is a force to be reckoned with here.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So I&#39;m glad you brought up retail. Some of the pushback I&#39;ve seen is the United States has been wildly over-retailed. I think in 2007, we had 24 square feet per capita versus Europe, which was like 14, and Japan, which was like 9. So we really had far more retailers than we knew what to do.</p><p> We built way too many malls and ultimately, this was going to go through a huge set of changes.</p><p> Anyway, private equity may be an accelerator a little bit, but we certainly can&#39;t blame the shrinking retail footprint on PE, can we?</p><p> MORGENSON: We can maybe put some of it on them, right, yes. And obviously, the shift to online hurt some folks, Toys R Us is an example of that.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right. And more recently, Bed Bath &amp; Beyond, that was a publicly traded company.</p><p> MORGENSON: That&#39;s right.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: They hit the wall without private equity&#39;s help.</p><p> So the biggest pushback I&#39;ve seen is, go back to the &#39;80s and &#39;90s when LBOs were first ramping up, companies went from big to really big. And as these big publicly traded mega companies went upmarket, the banks, the brokers, all of Wall Street chased them, and they just created this air pocket, this void underneath where there used to be national banks and national lenders servicing that industry, and they have nobody left to service them. And that vacuum is into what good private equity has stepped.</p><p> If it wasn&#39;t for the private equity below the four biggest companies, there&#39;s very little sources of capital for these $100, $500, $700 million firms that Wall Street ignores.</p><p> MORGENSON: Well, I think you have to say, then, if you&#39;re going to say, “Okay, these companies are not being banked properly,” then that&#39;s great if you can get money from private equity. But let&#39;s not bankrupt them in the process. You have a study that shows that bankruptcies occur far more with companies that are private equitized than it does with other companies.</p><p> So I think that, yes, if you want to have the resources, the capital is not being assigned to these companies, but that doesn&#39;t mean that they should be abused or that some of these practices can&#39;t be questioned.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: And one of my favorite parts of the book, you talk about equity ownership and wealth ownership in the United States. In 1913, the bottom 90% of incomes owned about 15% of the wealth in the United States. This is real estate, businesses, and publicly traded companies. By the &#39;80s, that had more than doubled to 35% of the wealth in the US Was that the peak? What happened with that going forward?</p><p> MORGENSON: That was the peak. And one of the reasons for that very big considerable growth and that was the, you know, people were able to have a family without having two wage earners….</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> MORGENSON: You were able to buy a house, et cetera. That moment in time, also a huge contributor to that was pensions. So corporate pensions that gave a worker a reasonable shot at a prosperous retirement.</p><p> And those started disappearing in the mid to late &#39;80s. And so that&#39;s a big factor in why the wealth held by the Main Street America, the middle class, the big broad brush America. That&#39;s why that has declined.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So here&#39;s, I think, my favorite pushback to the conversation about wealth inequality, and I&#39;m curious as to your thoughts. It&#39;s not the top 10% versus the bottom 90% where that big disparity has opened up. It&#39;s not even the top 1% versus the bottom 99%, although that&#39;s certainly pretty meaty.</p><p> It&#39;s the top 0.01% versus even within the top 1%, there&#39;s this massive disparity. We didn&#39;t used to have that many billionaires and uberwealthy today versus 50, 100 years ago. How has the distribution of wealth shifted in the United States and what might come out of that going forward?</p><p> MORGENSON: I just don&#39;t think it&#39;s a good thing to have this coterie of extreme, extreme wealth at the top of the pyramid. I mean, it&#39;s just not healthy. An economy does better if the most people are prosperous, right? And so these multi, multi, multi-billionaires are really outliers, but it points to a problem with the entire society.</p><p> And perhaps it&#39;s because we laud wealthy people, but part of it is this tax loophole that really is unfair. Part of it is some of the practices that really are aggressive and that end up harming companies and workers and pensioners. And let&#39;s not forget the huge fees that pensions pay to buy into private equity funds. And for years, those private equity funds outperformed the S&amp;P, but they no longer do.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So let&#39;s hit on that, because that&#39;s really interesting. This was a small asset class that, whether it was the illiquidity premium or just the ability to go places where the public markets couldn&#39;t, actually did better than the markets.</p><p> That risk premia seems to have evaporated.</p><p> MORGENSON: It stopped outperforming in like the mid-2000s or towards 2008. And so you really have to wonder what the purpose of the continued infatuation with private equity among pensions is if they can get the same return in a S&amp;P 500 with five basis points as a cost.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> MORGENSON: And total transparency, by the way, and a mark-to-market that you see at the end of every business day. And so, you know where you stand. So, it&#39;s not one of these fuzzy math situations where you don&#39;t really know what the value of the fund is because it&#39;s got private companies in it that are being marked by individuals who have an ax to grind in the mark.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Really quite interesting.</p><p> So, let me give you one of my curveball questions I like to surprise guests with. Your career history is “Money Magazine” in the early, mid-18th Davies, and then “Forbes” and then “Worth” magazine. But while you were at “Forbes” in 1995, you get tapped to be press secretary for then presidential election candidate Steve Forbes? What was that like? How different are political campaigns from covering finance?</p><p> MORGENSON: Well, when Steve asked me to be his press secretary, I thought, “Wow, this this is going to be interesting. I even maybe thought this is going to be fun.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> MORGENSON: Now I&#39;m a financial reporter, I am not a Washington reporter, I&#39;m not a political reporter, and so I had a different idea of what it might be like, but anyway, it was a very, very tough six months period.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: I can imagine.</p><p> MORGENSON: And it was, so Steve was a candidate that had economic ideas, okay?</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Flat tax, that was his big–</p><p> MORGENSON: One of them was the flat tax, which by the way would have gotten rid of lobbyists. That was the big benefit.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: And all those loopholes, right?</p><p> MORGENSON: Flat tax, he was also for medical savings accounts and health savings accounts. Anyway, and so I would explain these concepts. And he was against the double taxation of dividends, which of course we have gotten rid of, I think.</p><p> Anyway, so those were sort of three of his initial ideas. And I would have to explain these to the Washington Press Corps, the Washington Press Corps not being financially oriented and probably not that interested. They were just interested in the horse race.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Always, even to this day.</p><p> MORGENSON: Now, he did very well in New Hampshire, and so for a frenzied moment, it was like, maybe he has a chance or a shot. But anyway, it was a very trying time for me, but I really became a better journalist because of it.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: I was going to go there with that question. What was it like being on the other side of the clamoring, that scrum that you always see the photos of? How did that change how you do journalism and view journalists?</p><p> MORGENSON: Well, I really, after that, decided that I really wanted to give people a lot more time to respond to my questions because I would be asked to answer questions that were quite comprehensive and/or tricky, difficult to come up with the answer in minutes.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> MORGENSON: And so it was very frustrating to not be able to do that. And so I came away from that experience saying, okay, from now on, I&#39;m going to give everybody that I&#39;m writing about more time to respond because I don&#39;t want to put them in the situation that I was in.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: All right, we only have you for a few more minutes. Let me jump to my favorite questions that we ask all of our guests, starting with, tell us what you&#39;re streaming. What are you watching, listening to? What&#39;s keeping you entertained?</p><p> MORGENSON: What am I streaming? Well, gosh, I really like the BBC show “Happy Valley” I don&#39;t know if you&#39;ve seen that.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: No.</p><p> MORGENSON: It&#39;s kind of a detective, a pretty tough female detective, I like that. I like “Ted Lasso.”</p><p> RITHOLTZ: What&#39;s not to love?</p><p> MORGENSON: I know that&#39;s very mundane, but. So those are the two right now.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Tell us about mentors. Who helped shape your career?</p><p> MORGENSON: Jim Michaels, who was the editor of “Forbes” magazine. He was a very tough, old newspaper reporter. He was at UPI, and he was the guy who broke the story of Gandhi&#39;s assassination. So really knew how to do that kind of reporting. But he took his expertise to business and really taught me how to look at businesses, analyze balance sheets, income statements, really do contrarian reporting. He was a guy who didn&#39;t want the conventional wisdom. He wanted to question the conventional wisdom.</p><p> He was very difficult, very irascible, very demanding, but you really learned a lot.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Interesting. Let&#39;s talk about books. What are some of your favorites and what have you been reading recently?</p><p> MORGENSON: I like 19th century fiction. So Anthony Trollope, “The Way We Live Now” which is a really wonderful book about a tycoon who is sort of a scoundrel, who sells shares in a railroad company that doesn&#39;t really exist.</p><p>反正…</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Well, if you want the railroad to exist, that&#39;ll cost you more.</p><p> MORGENSON: Yes. Right now, I&#39;m actually reading a biography of Genghis Khan.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Oh, which one?</p><p> MORGENSON: Jack Weatherford.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: I&#39;m not sure if that&#39;s the one I read, but it&#39;s amazing.</p><p> MORGENSON: Yes, and that&#39;s a guy who was kind of slimed as being this terrible marauder and everything. It&#39;s a different story altogether, so I&#39;m really enjoying that.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Our last two questions. What sort of advice would you give to a recent college grad who is interested in a career in either investigative journalism or finance?</p><p> MORGENSON: Well, I would, of course, say go with investigative reporting because I think we need more of it in this country. I think we don&#39;t have as much as we need. We have seen newspapers hollowed out, of course.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Closed down left and right.</p><p> MORGENSON: Closed down. We&#39;ve also seen that the costs associated with investigative reporting, it&#39;s not easy. It&#39;s not something that happens overnight. So it really is costly and we&#39;ve seen that fewer and fewer of those folks.</p><p> So I would say gung ho if you can get a job doing that, that it is going to be the most fun that you&#39;re going to have and also doing a service.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: And what do you know about the world of investigative reporting and finance today you wish you knew back in the early 80s when you were first getting started?</p><p> MORGENSON: Well, let&#39;s see. So what&#39;s about the world of finance that I wish I knew 30 years ago is that it isn&#39;t as hard as you think. That it isn&#39;t, you know, a lot of people come out of college if they&#39;re not a financial person, like I was a humanities major, you know, and you have this mental block about numbers, I can&#39;t do numbers, or I, you know, it&#39;s not that hard. It really isn&#39;t that hard, it&#39;s common sense.</p><p> Now there are people who are really extra special good at it but, you know, it&#39;s something that you can tackle. Don&#39;t feel like you have a mental block against finance and don&#39;t think that finance isn&#39;t important. Finance is not a backwater, it touches everyone. It touches everybody in this country. It is political. It is everywhere. And so just don&#39;t discount the importance of finance. –</p><p> RITHOLTZ：真的很有趣。 Thank you, Gretchen, for being so generous with your time.</p><p> We have been speaking with Gretchen Morgenson. She is the author of “These Are the Plunderers, How Private Equity Runs and Wrecks America.”</p><p> If you enjoy this conversation, well, be sure and check out any of the previous 500 we&#39;ve done over the past, I don&#39;t know, eight years. You can find those on YouTube, iTunes, Spotify, or wherever you find your favorite podcasts.</p><p> Sign up for my daily reading list at ritholtz.com. Follow me on Twitter @Ritholtz. Follow all of the Bloomberg family of podcasts @podcast.</p><p> I would be remiss if I did not thank the crack team that helps put these conversations together each week. Sara Livezey is my audio engineer. Atika Valbrun is my project manager. Paris Wald is my producer. Sean Russo is my researcher. I&#39;m Barry Ritholtz, you&#39;ve been listening to Masters in Business on Bloomberg Radio.</p><p> END</p><p></p><p style="text-align: center;"> ~~~ </p><p></p><p><iframe style="width: 100%; max-width: 660px; overflow: hidden; background: transparent;" src="https://embed.podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/masters-in-business/id730188152" height="450" frameborder="0" sandbox="allow-forms allow-popups allow-same-origin allow-scripts allow-storage-access-by-user-activation allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation" data-mce-fragment="1"></iframe></p><p> The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://ritholtz.com/2023/06/transcript-gretchen-morgenson/">Transcript: Gretchen Morgenson</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://ritholtz.com">The Big Picture</a> .</p> ;
 10 Tuesday AM Reads https://ritholtz.com/2023/06/10-tuesday-am-reads-431/Barry Ritholtz Tue, 20 Jun 2023 10:30:21 +0000Links https://ritholtz.com/?p=314797 <p> My Two-for-Tuesday morning train WFH reads: • Attitudes have shifted in 3 major ways: 1. The Fed has become less hawkish, 2. The economy has become less likely to go into recession, 3. The stock market is not doomed to crater. (TKer) • How Cheap (or Expensive) is the Stock Market Right Now? Things look…</p><p> <a class="button" href="https://ritholtz.com/2023/06/10-tuesday-am-reads-431/">Read More<i class="icon ion-arrow-right-c"></i></a></p><p> The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://ritholtz.com/2023/06/10-tuesday-am-reads-431/">10 Tuesday AM Reads</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://ritholtz.com">The Big Picture</a> .</p> ; <p> My Two-for-Tuesday morning<del>火车</del>WFH reads:</p><blockquote><p> • <strong>Attitudes have shifted in 3 major ways</strong> : 1. The Fed has become less hawkish, 2. The economy has become less likely to go into recession, 3. The stock market is not doomed to crater. ( <a href="https://www.tker.co/p/market-economy-fed-attitudes-shifting" target="_blank" rel="noopener">TKer</a> )</p><p> • <strong>How Cheap (or Expensive) is the Stock Market Right Now?</strong> Things look a tad rich relative to the past 25 years but more or less in line with the averages. ( <a href="https://awealthofcommonsense.com/2023/06/how-cheap-or-expensive-is-the-stock-market-right-now/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">A Wealth of Common Sense</a> ) <em>see also</em> <strong>A Bull or a Bear Market? It Doesn&#39;t Matter</strong> . Stocks still haven&#39;t returned to their last peak, and our columnist is in the camp that says this isn&#39;t a bull market yet. But he&#39;s buying stock anyway. （ <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/16/business/bull-bear-market-investors.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">纽约时报</a>）</p><p> • <strong>Why People Are Still Splurging Even as Inflation Bites</strong> : A Harris Poll labeled the scrimp/splurge phenomenon a “split-brain” budget, but others have called it “the lipstick effect.” That&#39;s because research has shown that lipstick sales tend to pop during recessions, even when consumer spending is otherwise depressed. Buying decisions are less a matter of “or” but “and,” according to McKinsey, a pattern often seen during economic downturns. （ <a href="https://www.barrons.com/articles/inflation-americans-splurging-lipstick-effect-5687f834" target="_blank" rel="noopener">巴伦周刊</a>）</p><p> • <strong>Zombie Mortgages Could Force Some Homeowners Into Foreclosure</strong> : Homeowners say they are getting bills and foreclosure threats on second mortgages they thought were taken care of long ago. ( <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/zombie-mortgages-could-force-some-homeowners-into-foreclosure-e615ab2a" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Wall Street Journal</a> ) <em>see also</em> <strong>A $1.5 Trillion Backstop for Homebuyers Props Up Banks Instead</strong> : The Federal Home Loan Bank system provides billions to banks curtailing mortgage lending, and millions to its executives. ( <a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2023-06-04/us-effort-to-help-homebuyers-get-affordable-loans-mainly-benefits-banks-instead" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Businessweek</a> )</p><p> • <strong>What Really Brings People Back to the Office? The Easiest Commute</strong> . “One of the questions businesses are asking is &#39;How am I going to get my employees back into the office?&#39;” says Mike Slattery, director of tristate research at CBRE. “Part of that is providing light and air, more attractive amenities, and a really good location. On the other hand, if you can&#39;t offer your workers all those bells and whistles, at least you can give them an office close to transit.” ( <a href="https://www.curbed.com/2023/06/grand-central-offices-return-to-office-commutes.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Curbed</a> )</p><p> • <strong>The Moral Crisis of America&#39;s Doctors</strong> : The corporatization of health care has changed the practice of medicine, causing many physicians to feel alienated from their work. ( <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/15/magazine/doctors-moral-crises.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">New York Times</a> ) <em>see also</em> <strong>Documents show how conservative doctors influenced abortion, trans rights</strong> . A small group of conservative doctors has sought to shape the nation&#39;s most contentious policies on abortion and transgender rights by promoting views <em>rejected by the medical establishment</em> as scientific fact. After long struggling to attract members, the American College of Pediatricians gained outsize political influence in recent years, primarily by using conservative media as a megaphone in its quest to position the group as a reputable source of information., ( <a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2023/06/15/abortion-transgender-christian-doctors/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Washington Post</a> )</p><p> • <strong>Customer Ratings Have Become Meaningless. &#39;People Hand Out 5 Stars Like It&#39;s Candy.&#39;</strong> Riddled with confusion and guilt, Americans are handing out perfect Uber and Airbnb scores; &#39;Don&#39;t have to earn it anymore.&#39; （ <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/uber-airbnb-ratings-perfect-scores-customers-93686deb" target="_blank" rel="noopener">华尔街日报</a>）</p><p> • <strong>The dozens of attorneys who have defended Trump since 2016</strong> : Trump seems to have an unusual number of lawyers, and seems to move quickly through those lawyers. He has an unusual number of legal issues – two special counsel investigations, two impeachments, a criminal conviction for his company and a criminal indictment in Manhattan and dozens of other civil suits. ( <a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2023/06/16/trump-lawyers-legal-cases-explained/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Washington Post</a> ) <em>see also</em> <strong>Oath Keepers attorney is found incompetent to stand trial in Jan. 6 case</strong> : A volunteer for Lawyers for Trump, Kellye SoRelle became Oath Keepers leader Stewart Rhodes&#39;s girlfriend and a key post-2020 election contact with &#39;Stop the Steal&#39; groups So much incompetence to go with all the stupid. ( <a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/dc-md-va/2023/06/16/sorelle-incompetent-trial-oathkeepers-jan6/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Washington Post</a> )</p><p> • <strong>&#39;Bull Durham&#39; turns 35: Revisiting the most famous mound visit in baseball movie history</strong> : It&#39;s the present people have come to expect from someone behind one of the most famous scenes in sports movie history. Pitching coach Larry Hockett&#39;s sage advice during a meeting on the mound — “candlesticks always make a nice gift” — remains one of the most-quoted lines from the cinematic love letter to the minor leagues. ( <a href="https://theathletic.com/4604512/2023/06/15/bull-durham-35th-anniversary/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Athletic</a> )</p></blockquote><p>请务必查看我们本周末与 NBC 新闻和《华尔街日报》前记者格雷琴·摩根森 (Gretchen Morgenson) 的<a href="https://mailchi.us3.list-manage.com/track/click?u=383aaca5ff52f014f446ef1d2&amp;id=84d6a9bbfb&amp;e=6a376a9ff3" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?q=https://mailchi.us3.list-manage.com/track/click?u%3D383aaca5ff52f014f446ef1d2%26id%3D84d6a9bbfb%26e%3D6a376a9ff3&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1686913661139000&amp;usg=AOvVaw0UA1iGMP_RLUFA3lEaWcdJ">商业硕士</a><a href="https://mailchi.us3.list-manage.com/track/click?u=383aaca5ff52f014f446ef1d2&amp;id=171e6b4958&amp;e=6a376a9ff3" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?q=https://mailchi.us3.list-manage.com/track/click?u%3D383aaca5ff52f014f446ef1d2%26id%3D171e6b4958%26e%3D6a376a9ff3&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1686913661139000&amp;usg=AOvVaw0GqVGJoMP6Nj_30DRCg0cn">访谈</